Kenya has recorded 18 new COVID-19 cases from
2,086 samples tested in the last 24 hours, marking a positivity rate of 0.9 per
cent. Of the cases, 13 are Kenyans and 5 are
foreigners; 10 are males while 8 are females. The youngest is a 9- year-old
child while the oldest is 63 years old. Total confirmed positive cases are now
323,664 and cumulative tests so far conducted are 3,576,023. In terms of county distribution, Nairobi had
16 cases, Garissa and Trans Nzoia one case each. In the vaccination campaign, a total of
17,837,914 vaccines had been administered across the country as of April 20,
2022. "Of these, 16,313,182 are doses
administered to the adult population (18 years and above),” Health Cabinet
Secretary Mutahi Kagwe said in a statement to newsrooms on Thursday. “Another 1,231,273 are doses administered to
those between 15 to 17 years, while 293,459 are booster doses.” The CS added that the total number of
vaccines administered in the last 24 hours is 8,425 while the total number of
people fully vaccinated is 5,498. The proportion of adults fully vaccinated is
30.3 per cent, he said, adding that the government is working towards
vaccinating a targeted population of 2,246,033. Kagwe noted that no patient recovered from
the disease, thus the total recoveries are still at 317,851. No death was recorded either, thus the
cumulative fatalities stand at 5,649. A total of three patients are currently
admitted to various health facilities countrywide, while 130 are under the Home-Based
Isolation and Care program.  “No patient is in the Intensive Care Unit
(ICU) or on supplemental oxygen or in the general wards. No patient is in the
High Dependency Unit (HDU),” Kagwe said.